From the pairplot we can see a few peculiar/interesting things:¶
    

  1. I would hope that the suicide rate decreases each year but it looks like it does not. We can see that the level of suicide numbers of groups (year, country, age, sex group) increase, although the peak was somewhere around 1994.
    

    2. 

  2. One would expect all populations to stricly increase as years increase since the measuring interval of the population is a WHOLE year but the one group with the most people have a peak and then decrease for a few years.
    

    3. 

  3. As expected, both GDPs increase each year.
    

    4. 

  4. The suicide_no x population pairplot does keep the trend of more people means more suicides (as could be seen in the pandas profiling, since these variables are positively correlated), however the peak in the middle is kind of unexpected? It probably is the same group that has the highest suicide number.
    

    5. 

  5. The GPD per capita after reaching a certain threshold drop the number of suicides a lot (pairplot[1, 4]). There are a few countries that look like they would continue to increase.

Visualization of suicide_no distributions dependant on different categorical variables¶
One cannot compare the absolute values of suicide numbers because of the fact that as stated above, the more people, the more absolute proportion of the people can commit suicide. Therefore we have to normalize the suicides first. We normalize them and show the numbers per 100k people of the given group we create.













In [9]:



    


'''top 20 Countries in suicides'''
countries = data.groupby("country").sum().reset_index()
countries["suicides_per_100k"] = (countries["suicides_no"] / countries["population"]) * 100000
plt.figure(figsize=(20,10))
plt.title("top 20 countries with the highest suicide rates")
sns.barplot(x="suicides_per_100k", y="country", data=countries.sort_values("suicides_per_100k").tail(20))

''' Continents x Suicides '''
cont = data.groupby("continent").sum().reset_index()

''' Checking whether Europes suicides per 100k is really the highest because of the Russian federation'''
no_russia = data[data["country"] != "Russian Federation"]
cont = no_russia.groupby("continent").sum().reset_index()
cont["suicides_per_100k"] = (cont["suicides_no"] / cont["population"]) * 100000
plt.figure(figsize=(20,10))
sns.barplot(x="continent", y="suicides_per_100k", data=cont)
# removing The Russian Federation from the dataset pretty much equals out Europe and Asia. That is however still not to be expected. From my own bubble of social media, 
# I hear that Asian people commit suicides lots. Therefore I expected Asia to be way above Europe.

Clustering¶
We try clustering suicides number with the gdp per capita as that could find out the suicide rate per gdp per capita group













In [15]:



    


from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler


'''After scaling the data, we find the optimal number of clusters with the elbow method.'''
data["suicides_per_100k"] = (data["suicides_no"] / data["population"]) * 100000
country = data.groupby("country").mean().reset_index()
gdp_sui = country[["gdp_per_capita", "suicides_per_100k", "country"]]
scaler = MinMaxScaler()
transformed_gdp_sui = scaler.fit_transform(gdp_sui[["gdp_per_capita", "suicides_per_100k"]])

losses = []
for i in range(1, 11):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=i)
    kmeans.fit(transformed_gdp_sui)
    losses.append(kmeans.inertia_)
sns.set()
plt.figure(figsize=(20,10))
sns.lineplot(range(10), losses)

kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=4)

labels = kmeans.predict(transformed_gdp_sui) 
df = pd.DataFrame(pd.concat([pd.DataFrame(transformed_gdp_sui, columns={"gdp_per_capita", "suicides_per_100k"}), pd.DataFrame(labels, columns={"labels"})], axis=1))
df["country"] = gdp_sui["country"]
plt.figure(figsize=(20,10))
sns.scatterplot(x="gdp_per_capita", y="suicides_per_100k", hue="labels", data=df, palette="Set2")
plt.xlabel("country mean gdp_per_capita")
plt.ylabel("country mean suicide_per_100k")

def label_point(x, y, val, ax):
    a = pd.concat({'x': x, 'y': y, 'val': val}, axis=1)
    for i, point in a.iterrows():
        ax.text(point['x']+0.01, point['y'], str(point['val']))

label_point(df["gdp_per_capita"], df["suicides_per_100k"], df["country"], plt.gca())  



    















    




























From this graph we cannot really find a relationship between country mean gdp per capita and country mean suicides rate. One would guess that the more gdp_per_capita the less suicides, but as we can see e.g. Switzerland or Luxembourg, that doesn't really seem like it.

Discussion¶
We now know how the dataset behaves. The Europeans have the highest suicide rates, although that might not be statistically significant as we have more European data than e.g. Asian data (although the normalized version proposes that Europeans do in fact commit more suicides). We found that the suicide number is positively correlated with gpd_for_year but not gpd_per_capita (without a p-value though). The Russian Federation has the highest absolute number of suicides, while Lithuania has the most suicides per 100k people. We have seen that throughout time, men commited more suicides each year. We found out that the eldest have the highest probability of commiting suicide, both by age/year and generation. This suggests to not use the generation variable as it can be calculated given a year and the age group. We then studied the Japan and South Korea suicide relationship.
